Background

Baseball is considered Americas Pasttime (however, the instructor does not share this perspective and personally finds the game boring). Like many other sporting events, the game generates a lot of data at both the player and team levels. Some rare events in baseball include pitching a no-hitter (a game without a hit) and hitting a grand slam (a home run while 3 people on base). In the five seasons between 2006 and 2010, the average number of grand slams per team per season was only about 4. We will be using data gathered from the Major League Baseball (MLB) website throughout this exam. The data can be found on the course site (MLB final data.csv).

The data set contains measurements on several commonly recorded statistics for the 30 Major League Baseball teams:

  • Team.Name: name of team.
  • Short.Name: shortened version of team name.
  • GrSlam: total number of grand slams (home runs with bases loaded)
  • Cycles: total number of cycles (when a player hits at least one single, double, triple, and home run in one game)
  • League: indicator of league; AL = American League, NL = National League
  • Games: total number of games played
  • At.Bats: number of players who came to the plate to hit in the given timeframe
  • Runs: runs scored
  • Hits: number of times the batter safely reached first base after hitting the ball into fair territory, without the benefit of an error or a fielders choice.
  • Doubles: doubles hit
  • Triples: triples hit
  • Hm.Runs: home runs
  • RBI: runs batted in (runs scored and credited to the batter)
  • TB: total number of bases, calculated by summing 1 for each single, 2 for each double, 3 for each triple, and 4 for each home run
  • BB: base on balls (walks due to 4 balls thrown by pitcher)
  • SO: strikeouts (3 strikes)
  • SB: stolen bases (runner advances without a hit or walk)
  • CS: caught stealing (runner tried to steal base and got thrown out)
  • OBP: on-base percentage (tht total number of hits, bases on balls, and times hit by pitch, divided by the total number of at-bats, bases on balls, times hit by pitch, and sacrifice flies).
  • SLG: slugging percentage (the total bases recorded by the batter, divided by the total number of at-bats)
  • AVG: batting average (the number of base hits, divided by the total number of at-bats)

The values for the variables GrSlam, Cycles and Games are count totals over five seasons from 2006 to 2010. The values for the remaining variables are averages over the five seasons. Full descriptions of abbreviations and acronyms can be found at

http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/official_info/baseball_basics/abbreviations.jsp

Problem 2 (Functions)

Suppose we were interested in determining which features are highly correlated with the number of grand slams a team has over five seasons. For example, the correlation between the number of grand slams and the number of funs a teams scores would be given by

cor(GrSlam, Runs)

which results in a value of approximately 0.4. Further, it would be nice to order the features based on their correlation with the number of grand slams obtained.

Construct a function corOrder(x, y) which takes a vector x and a matrix y comprised of numeric variables (so, variables like League are not considered). It returns a matrix of dimension nrow(y)-by-2; the first column contains values corresponding to the columns of y and the second column contains the correlation between the corresponding column of y and the vector x. More, the matrix shoud be sorted in decreasing correlation values.

Problem 7 (Simulation)

The on base percentage (OBP) for a player is an estimate of the probability the player will get on base when stepping up to bat. The OBP variable reported in the MLB data is the average of the on base percentage for all players on the team over the five seasons observed. Therefore, it is not a true representation of an individuals performance. For example, for the Chicago Cubs, the OBP in the MLB dataset is 0.3316. However, individuals on the team will vary about that value. Suppose we are willing to make the following assumptions:

  • Let \(X_i\) be the OBP for the \(i\)-th individual on a team.
  • \(X_i \sim N(\mu, 0.06^2)\) where \(\mu\) is the average OBP for the team.
  • The players up to bat in an inning are randomly chosen from the team.
  • Players only get out if they strike out.
  • The inning continues until there are three outs.

Admittedly, these are unrealistic assumptions. However, under these assumptions, write a small simulation that examines the distribution of the number of batters the Cubs will send up in the inning will see before it ends. Problem 8 (Randomization-Based Inference)

Suppose we want to compare the number of grand slams over the 5 seasons recorded for the American and National Leagues. A standard approach would be to construct a 95% confidence interval for \(\mu_1 - \mu_2\) where \(\mu_1\) is the average number of grand slams for an American League team and \(\mu_2\) is the average number of grand slams for a National League team. We might do this using a t-interval, for example: \[\bar{y}_1 - \bar{y}_2 \pm t_{df, 0.975} \sqrt{s_1^2/n_1 + s_2^2/n_2}\]

which is based on modeling the ratio \[\frac{\left(\bar{y}_1 - \bar{y}_2\right) - \left(\mu_1 - \mu_2\right)}{\sqrt{s_1^2/n_1 + s_2^2/n_2}}\]

using a t-distribution. However, this model requires the assumption that each of the two populations follows a Normal distribution. This is a limiting assumption. Write a bootstrapping algorithm to compute a 95% confidence interval for the difference in the average number of grand slams achieved for the two leagues. Your interval should roughly equal:

     2.5%     97.5% 
-4.125223  5.205357
